          "body": "The prayer ends with two Hebrew words: *yeshuatah la-Yhwh* — *salvation belongs to Yahweh* (2:9). The line is the theological summit of the book and one of the great compressed creeds of the Old Testament. Yeshuah (the same root that names Joshua and Jesus) is Yahweh's exclusive possession; no co-savior, no human contribution, no idol shares the verb. The line is Jonah's most orthodox utterance — and the chapter's irony. Jonah confesses pure monergism for himself but in chapter 4 will resent that the same monergism extends to Nineveh. The doctrine is right; the heart has not yet caught up. This is the chapter's pastoral warning: theological precision and full repentance are not the same thing. The prayer of 2:9 is true. It is not yet complete."
